  <static seed="569" source="PCC-ORCCA-ed3/BasicAlgebra/GraphingQuadratics/ParabolaIntercepts30.pg">
    <statement><p>Find the <m>y</m>-intercept and any <m>x</m>-intercept(s) of the quadratic curve.</p>
<p><m>{y}={x^{2}-25}</m></p>
<p><m>y</m>-intercept: <fillin characters="16" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
<p><m>x</m>-intercept(s): <fillin characters="17" name="AnSwEr0002"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(0,-25\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(-5,0\right), \left(5,0\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To find a parabola<rsq/>s <m>y</m>-intercept, we substitute <m>x=0</m> into <m>{y}={x^{2}-25}</m>, and we have <m>y=-25</m>.</p>
<p>The parabola<rsq/>s <m>y</m>-intercept is <m>(0,-25)</m>.</p>
<p>To find a parabola<rsq/>s <m>x</m>-intercept, we substitute <m>y=0</m> into <m>{y}={x^{2}-25}</m>, and then solve for <m>x</m>.</p>
<p>For this problem, notice that the polynomial can be factored by the difference of squares formula:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}[t]
   y \amp = {x^{2}-25} \\
   0 \amp = {x^{2}-25} \\
   0 \amp = (x + 5)(x-5) \\
   x + 5 \amp = 0      \amp \text{or} \amp \amp  x-5 \amp = 0 \\
   x       \amp = -5  \amp \text{or} \amp \amp  x \amp = 5 
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The parabola<rsq/>s <m>x</m>-intercepts are <m>(-5,0)</m> and <m>(5,0)</m>.</p>
</solution>
